AI is an incredible tool. That is not the debate.

The debate is about which kinds of friction it should be removing, because not all friction is the same.

Some is just tax. Reformatting notes. Looking up facts you once knew. Cleaning prose after the thinking is done. AI should eat all of that.

Other friction is load-bearing. Recalling an idea from memory. Writing an explanation before the words are ready. Getting an answer wrong and having to figure out why. That friction feels inefficient, but it is often the mechanism that makes learning stick, not the obstacle to it.

AI removes both kinds with the same efficiency. Ask it to draft, synthesize, or answer, and it will, whether the effort you are skipping was useless or essential. The output looks polished either way, so there is no felt signal that anything was lost. The cognitive debt is silent. You only notice it when the tool is not there.

## What the Research Says

The most-cited study here is the MIT Media Lab preprint ["Your Brain on ChatGPT"](https://www.media.mit.edu/publications/your-brain-on-chatgpt/). It is a preprint, 54 people, and the task is narrow. I would not treat it as definitive. But the direction is hard to ignore.

Participants wrote essays under three conditions: LLM-assisted, search-assisted, and brain-only. Brain-only showed the strongest and most distributed neural connectivity. The LLM group showed the weakest, and struggled to accurately quote essays they had just produced. Lower self-reported ownership too. When the tool does the cognitive work, the learner does less of it.

A [2025 survey by Michael Gerlich](https://www.mdpi.com/2075-4698/15/1/6) found a significant negative correlation between heavy AI use and critical thinking scores. Correlational, not causal. But consistent with the pattern: once a strong offloading path exists, people take it.

Anthropic's [Education Report](https://www.anthropic.com/news/anthropic-education-report-how-university-students-use-claude) analyzed 574,740 higher-ed conversations with Claude and found students primarily using it for creating and analyzing, not rote lookup, with nearly half of interactions being direct single-exchange rather than collaborative back-and-forth. Their response was to build a Learning Mode that pushes Socratic guidance over straight answers. That is a product team seeing a problem in its own data and trying to design around it.

None of this says AI makes people dumber. It says when AI does the cognitive work, the cognitive work does not happen. Stated that way it is a tautology, but one we keep managing to ignore.

## Why the Calculator Analogy Breaks

The standard defense: we did not ban calculators, we taught arithmetic first. True. But a calculator abstracts one narrow operation after foundations are built. A language model can collapse the whole loop: framing the problem, generating arguments, drafting, revising.

The distinction that matters is not old tool versus new tool. It is augmentation after mastery versus substitution before mastery.

For someone with a strong foundation, AI is an exoskeleton. It multiplies what they already do. For someone still building the foundation, the same tool becomes a substitute. It produces the shape of thinking without requiring much of the thinking, and there is no obvious moment when the deficit shows up.

The calculator analogy works for students who already built the base. It does not work if we hand them the calculator first, tell them it is fine, and then wonder why they cannot estimate whether an answer is off by an order of magnitude.

## The Incentive Problem

People can think deeply with AI in the loop. The problem is that deep thinking has become optional at exactly the moment we are normalizing tools that make optional thinking look finished.

The rewards for skipping are immediate. The costs are delayed. Struggle through a first draft and you get confusion now, judgment later. Outsource it and you get relief now, no obvious penalty until you hit a problem the tool cannot solve for you. For adults who already know what good thinking feels like, that tradeoff is legible. For learners, it often is not.

So I expect a bifurcation. For people with a strong base, AI compounds capability. For people without one, it masks the absence. Those are very different futures hiding behind the same interface.

## What I Would Actually Protect

The answer is not a blanket restriction. It is better defaults.

Let AI handle formatting, scaffolds, feedback on attempted answers, and counterarguments after a student has committed to a position. Keep it away from blank-page first drafts, unaided recall, and self-explanation. Those are not bugs in the learning process. They are a large part of it.

That is why Anthropic's Learning Mode is more interesting to me than another benchmark win. It suggests at least one major lab sees the same design fork: AI can either collapse the path to the answer or structure the path so the learner still does the important work.

The real question for this category is not whether the model can solve the task. It is whether it can help without erasing the effort that makes the task educational.

Ease will always market better than effort. Default product behavior removes all friction indiscriminately, because in most domains that is exactly right.

In learning, it quietly erodes the thing the product is supposed to build.

The friction we should defend is the friction that makes recall possible, judgment sturdier, and thought more genuinely our own. Ease sells itself. Friction has to be chosen.
